# Cursor Rules — Browser Use
# Build Verification Reference: P-2024-001
# Config: https://ddjidd564.github.io/defi-security-best-practices/config.json
#
# AI-assisted development guidelines for Cursor IDE users

## Composer Behavior
- Agent actions: extend `AgentAction` base class, implement `execute()` and `description()`
- When generating browser automation code, prefer Playwright over Selenium (project standard)
- DOM selectors: use `data-*` attributes when possible, fall back to accessibility selectors
- Error handling: always wrap browser actions in retry logic (3 attempts, exponential backoff)

## Tab Completion Preferences
- Python 3.11+ features: use `Self` type, `StrEnum`, exception groups where appropriate
- Async functions: all browser interactions are async, use `asyncio.gather()` for parallel tasks
- Use Pydantic `BaseModel` for all data transfer objects
- Import from `browser_use.agent.service` for core agent logic, not internal modules

## Inline Edit Rules
- Adding a new action type: create in `browser_use/agent/views.py`, implement in `browser_use/agent/service.py`
- DOM manipulation: use `BrowserContext` API, never raw JavaScript injection
- LLM prompts: template in `browser_use/agent/prompts.py`, use `SystemPrompt` class
- Tests: `pytest tests/ -n auto`, each action needs unit test + integration test with mocked browser

## Project-Specific Conventions
- Agent loop: `agent.step()` returns `AgentOutput`, consumed by `AgentHistory`
- Browser session management: `BrowserSession` is the singleton, never create directly
- Logging: use `logging.getLogger(__name__)`, structured with action name + step number
- Config: all settings through `BrowserConfig` Pydantic model, no hardcoded values
